    <!--                  SECTION ONE: POLYGONAL REGIONS & AREA          -->
    <!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->

    <string name="SectionOneTheoryDef_14">• A polygonal region includes a polygon and its interior.
\n • Interior points belong to the region; exterior points do not.
\n • Figures with equal area are equivalent, not necessarily congruent.</string>

    <!-- Q: Can two figures be equivalent (equal area) without being congruent? Answer: True -->
    <string name="SectionOneTheoryDefQuestion_14">Can two figures have equal area without being congruent?</string>
    <string name="SectionOneTheoryDefAnswerOne_14">True</string>
    <string name="SectionOneTheoryDefAnswerTwo_14">False</string>
    <string name="SectionOneTheoryDefAnswerThree_14">Neither</string>
    <string name="SectionOneTheoryDefCorrectAnswer_14">True</string>

    <string name="SectionOneTheoryProperties_14">• Every polygon has a positive area.
\n • Congruent polygons have equal areas.
\n • Total area of a figure equals sum of its non-overlapping parts.
\n • Area of a square is the side squared.
\n • A part of a figure has area ≤ the whole figure.</string>

    <!-- Q: If the side of a square is 5, what is its area? Answer: 25 -->
    <string name="SectionOneTheoryPropsQuestion_14">If the side of a square is 5, what is its area?</string>
    <string name="SectionOneTheoryPropsAnswerOne_14">10</string>
    <string name="SectionOneTheoryPropsAnswerTwo_14">25</string>
    <string name="SectionOneTheoryPropsAnswerThree_14">20</string>
    <string name="SectionOneTheoryPropsCorrectAnswer_14">25</string>

    <string name="SectionOneTheoryWorkedExamples_14">• A complex polygon can be split into simpler non-overlapping parts: e.g. an L-shaped figure split into two rectangles of areas 12 and 8 gives a total area of 20.
\n • If the unit changes from cm to m (factor of 100), the numerical area value changes by 100², but the physical space stays the same.
\n • Two rectangles of dimensions 3×4 and 2×6 are not congruent, but both have area 12 — they are equivalent figures.</string>

    <!-- Q: A figure is split into parts with areas 12 and 8. What is the total area? Answer: 20 -->
    <string name="SectionOneTheoryWorkedExQuestion_14">A polygon is split into two non-overlapping parts with areas 12 and 8. What is the total area?</string>
    <string name="SectionOneTheoryWorkedExAnswerOne_14">16</string>
    <string name="SectionOneTheoryWorkedExAnswerTwo_14">96</string>
    <string name="SectionOneTheoryWorkedExAnswerThree_14">20</string>
    <string name="SectionOneTheoryWorkedExCorrectAnswer_14">20</string>

